==Old English==
===Etymology===
From West Germanic ''*biōr-'', from monastic Latin [[biber]] ‘drink’, from Latin [[bibere]] ‘to drink’ (French [[boire]] etc.).  Cognate with Old Frisian [[biar|biār]], Old Saxon [[bior]] (Dutch [[bier]]), Old High German [[bior]] (German [[Bier]]).

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /be:or/

===Noun===
'''bēor''' ''n''
# ''(Poetic)'' [[beer]], [[ale]]
#:''Gebeotedon beore druncne oret-mecgas, ðæt hie in beor-sele bidan wolde Grendles guðe'': The sons of conflict, drunk on beer, promised that they would wait in the beer-hall for Grendel’s attack.  (''Beowulf'')


